"""
MKT Context Layer — Song of Solomon chapters 7–8 (comprehensive)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-songofsolomon-7-8.py

27 verses: ch7=13, ch8=14
Context focus: wasf tradition in ANE love poetry; geographical references
(Heshbon, Damascus, Carmel, Baal-Hamon); teshuqah (7:10) as reversal
of Gen 3:16; seal/shalhevetyah passage (8:6-7) as ANE climax; brothers
as guardians institution; vineyard ownership motif through the book.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The second full <em>wasf</em> (Arabic: descriptive praise poem) of the Song, unique in running from feet to head — an ascending rather than descending survey. This reversal of the usual head-to-foot sequence (used in 4:1-7) is unparalleled in the surviving ANE love poetry corpus and may signal a new vantage point: the beloved is viewed in the context of a processional dance (<em>machola ha-machanayim</em>, the dance of the two camps, 6:13). The title <em>hassulammit</em> — the only proper name for the beloved in the Song — derives most likely from <em>Shlomo</em> (Solomon) as its feminine counterpart, or possibly from <em>shalom</em> (peace/wholeness), making her 'the peaceable one.' The thighs compared to jewels worked by a craftsman: in the ancient Near East, skilled craftsmen (<em>ben-aman</em>, son of a master, a technical guild title) produced ornamental metalwork worn as identity markers. The quality of sandals was a social indicator: only slaves went unshod (cf. the sandal-binding idiom in John 1:27; Mark 1:7), making sandaled feet a marker of free status and honor.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The <em>shorer</em> (H8326, navel/umbilical region, a hapax legomenon appearing only here) contributes to the challenge of this verse: it is either the navel itself or the curve of the abdomen. The comparison to an <em>'aggan</em> (H101, a mixing bowl for wine) — round and never lacking mixed wine — combines the visual image of a curved vessel with the sensory image of abundance. The belly like a heap of wheat (<em>aremah hittim</em>) surrounded by lilies is a landscape-to-body metaphor that appears frequently in Egyptian love poetry: the Papyrus Chester Beatty I (13th century BCE) parallels descriptions of the beloved's body using agricultural abundance imagery. The heap of wheat specifically recalls the threshing floor, the site of harvest abundance and — in biblical narrative — significant social encounters (Ruth 3; cf. also Hosea 9:1). The lily-bordered wheat image combines harvest plenty with garden delicacy in a deliberately rich sensory compound.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The twin-fawn simile for the breasts repeats 4:5 nearly verbatim: <em>shenei shadayikh kishenei ofarim te'omei tseviyah</em> (your two breasts are like two fawns, twins of a gazelle). The near-verbatim repetition within a single book is a recognized feature of ancient Near Eastern poetry — not a scribal error but a structural device of deliberate echo. The twin gazelle image is attested in Egyptian love poetry (Papyrus Harris 500, Song 2A) and in Ugaritic poetry for pairing of equals. Gazelle fawns were prized in the ancient Near East for their softness and the matching perfection of a twinned pair; the image captures both sensory gentleness and perfect symmetry. The deliberate internal echo between 4:5 and 7:3 creates a chiastic inclusio in the Song's central section, bracketing the <em>wasf</em> passages.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The geographical catalogue in 7:4 anchors the poem in specific, historically significant landscapes: Heshbon was the former Amorite royal city of King Sihon (Num 21:25-34), conquered by Israel in the Transjordanian campaign; the city and its pools are mentioned in Isaiah 16:8-9 as well. The pools of Heshbon (<em>breichot be-cheshbon</em>) at the gate of <em>bat-rabbim</em> (daughter of the multitude or daughter of many, H1337) were likely well-known irrigation features in the Transjordanian landscape. Damascus, the ancient capital of Aram/Syria, appears as a comparator for the nose — the prominent tower of Damascus toward Lebanon (<em>migdal levanon tsofeh penei dammaseq</em>) would have been recognizable to the audience as a landmark of the northern horizon. The ivory tower (<em>migdal ha-shen</em>) for the neck is the only ivory tower reference in the Hebrew Bible; ivory was an elite luxury material in the ancient Near East, associated with royal courts (1 Kings 22:39: Ahab's ivory house; Ps 45:8: ivory palaces).</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Ha-karmel</em> (H3760) is both the specific place name (Mount Carmel, the prominent coastal promontory running into the Mediterranean at modern Haifa) and the common noun meaning a cultivated garden-land or fertile field. Carmel's distinctive feature in the landscape was its dense forests and orchards contrasting with the surrounding terrain — Isaiah 35:2 uses Carmel as an image of exceptional beauty and abundance. The hair like purple (<em>velachur arganah</em>) is the color of royalty — Tyrian purple, the most expensive dye of the ancient world, extracted from Murex sea snails along the Phoenician coast. The final clause — <em>melekh asur ba-rehatim</em> (the king is held/captivated in the flowing locks) — uses <em>rahut</em> (H7298, flowing channels/troughs or possibly streaming locks) to suggest that the beloved's hair has entrapped the king as channels capture flowing water. The image of hair as a net/trap for the beloved appears in Egyptian love poetry and in Prov 7:21 (seductress).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The direct-address appreciation — <em>mah-yafet umah-na'amt ahavah bata'anugim</em> (how fair and how pleasant you are, O love, among delights) — steps back from the anatomical inventory of the <em>wasf</em> to offer the holistic impression. <em>Ta'anug</em> (H8588, delight, pleasantness, luxury) is used of royal luxury in Micah 1:16 and of the delights of Qohelet's life project in Ecclesiastes 2:8. The plural <em>bata'anugim</em> (among/with all your delights) may be a genitive of attendant characteristic: love itself as the supreme delight. In Egyptian love poetry (Papyrus Chester Beatty I), the holistic appreciation of the beloved — stepping back from the detailed description to exclaim about the whole — is a recognized formal transition in the <em>wasf</em> genre: detailed description followed by comprehensive appreciation is the standard pattern.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The date palm (<em>tamar</em>, H8558) was the economically dominant tree of the ancient Near East — the date palm was a symbol of Jericho (city of palms, Deut 34:3), of Mesopotamian abundance in Babylonian texts, and of beauty in Egyptian art. Palm trees were used as architectural motifs in Solomon's temple (1 Kings 6:29, 32, 35) and in Ezekiel's vision of the restored temple (Ezek 40:16-31). In the ancient Near East, the date palm was one of the tallest, most graceful, and most productive trees in the agricultural landscape; a woman's stature compared to a date palm invokes all of these associations — height, grace, and fruitfulness. The breasts compared to date clusters (<em>eshkolot</em>, H811, clusters of grapes or dates) continues the harvest-abundance vocabulary that characterizes this <em>wasf</em>.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The declaration that the bridegroom will ascend the palm tree (<em>e'eleh ba-tamar</em>, I will ascend by the palm tree) describes an actual practice: date palm climbing for harvest was performed by skilled workers in the ancient Near East, climbing with a rope-and-foot technique to reach the date clusters at the crown. The date harvest was a major agricultural and commercial event — dates were pressed into blocks for trade, fermented into date wine, and stored as a caloric staple. The clusters/boughs (<em>sansinav</em>, H5577, its branches or fruiting stalks, a hapax in this form) were the primary commercial product. The comparison of the beloved's breath to apples (<em>tapuchim</em>, H8598, apples or quince) continues the orchard-garden sensory vocabulary of the Song's consistent landscape, and the comparison of her mouth to the best wine sets up the transition to v9b where the beloved's own voice takes over.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The mid-verse voice transition — the beloved takes up the speech in mid-sentence — is a distinctive feature of the Song's use of multiple voices and is noted by virtually all commentators. <em>Holekh ledodi lemeyasharim dovev siftei yeshenim</em> (going down smoothly for my beloved, flowing over the lips of those who are asleep) — the wine-flowing image for speech that flows sweetly and easily, even rousing the sleeping. The <em>yeshenim</em> (H3463, those who are asleep/sleeping ones) in connection with wine has been interpreted as the lips of the sleeping beloved murmuring to the bridegroom even in sleep, or as wine that revives even sleepers. Egyptian love poetry uses the image of wine-smooth speech as a standard compliment for the beloved's voice, connecting the sensory pleasures of speech and wine.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>Teshuqah</em> (H8669, desire, longing) is one of the most theologically significant words in the Song. It appears only three times in the Hebrew Bible: Genesis 3:16 (the post-fall curse on the woman: 'your desire will be for your husband, and he will rule over you'), Genesis 4:7 (sin crouching at the door with desire for Cain), and here in 7:10. The Genesisoccurrences are both associated with distorted desire — the post-fall gender hierarchy and the desire of sin for the sinner. Song 7:10 — <em>ani ledodi ve'alai teshuqato</em> (I am my beloved's and his desire is for me) — represents the positive redemption of the term: desire that is mutual, reciprocal, and uncoerced. This is the only occurrence of <em>teshuqah</em> in the Bible where the desire is straightforwardly positive and restored, suggesting that the Song participates in the redemption of what the fall corrupted in Genesis 3.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The invitation to go out into the fields and lodge in the villages (<em>kefar</em>, H3723, villages/hamlets — the plural of the very common agricultural settlement unit) is the beloved's initiative — she invites the bridegroom into her pastoral world. The rural pastoral setting contrasts with the urban tensions in 3:1-5 and 5:7 (city watchmen, urban night-search scenes). In the ancient Near East, the agricultural village was the basic social unit; the invitation to lodge in the village rather than the city palace suggests an egalitarian intimacy outside the formal structures of royal court life. Egyptian love poetry frequently uses the garden and the rural estate as the setting for erotic encounter, contrasting the freedom of the open countryside with the formal constraints of the house/city.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The spring vineyard inspection — <em>nistrah hagefen pitach hasemadar heniczu ha-rimmonim</em> (whether the vine has budded, whether the tender grape blossom has opened, whether the pomegranates have bloomed) — repeats the spring-survey vocabulary of 2:13 almost exactly (<em>hagefanim semdar natenu reach</em>, the vines in blossom give off fragrance; the pomegranates in bloom). The deliberate verbal echo creates a seasonal cycle: what was described as a sign of spring's arrival (2:13) is now proposed as an occasion for the beloved to give her love. The vineyard as the setting for erotic encounter was a recognized literary convention in Egyptian love poetry (Papyrus Harris 500, Song 4: 'come, let us go to the field and make our bed in the garden'); the vineyard also carries its covenant connotations in the OT (Isa 5:1-7 uses the vineyard for YHWH and Israel).</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Duda'im</em> (H1736, mandrakes) are the <em>Mandragora officinarum</em>, a plant with fleshy fruit that grows in the Mediterranean region and has been associated with fertility and erotic stimulation in ancient Near Eastern popular belief. Mandrakes appear in Genesis 30:14-16, where Reuben finds them in the field during the wheat harvest and Rachel trades Jacob's company for Leah's mandrakes — a text that explicitly connects mandrakes with fertility desire. In ANE popular medicine, mandrakes were considered aphrodisiacs and fertility enhancers; the Akkadian term <em>nam-tar-gira</em> (love plant) may be a parallel. The 'new and old' stored fruits (<em>chadashim gam-yeshanim tsafanti lecha</em>, new things as well as old things I have stored up for you) suggests accumulated gifts across seasons — a long-term investment of love expressed in gathered fruit. The pattern of both new and old echoes the wisdom teacher's treasure in Matthew 13:52.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The wish — <em>mi yittencha ke'ach li</em> (who will give you to me as a brother) — uses the idiom <em>mi yitten</em> (if only! would that!) characteristic of Hebrew wishes for the impossible or deeply desired (cf. Job 14:13: 'Oh that you would hide me in Sheol'; Jer 9:1: 'Oh that my head were waters'). The underlying social constraint the wish expresses: in the ancient Near East, brothers and sisters could display physical affection publicly (the kiss of greeting was socially sanctioned within the family), but romantic couples showing public affection invited censure. Deuteronomy 22:28-29 and related texts indicate that unmarried couples meeting privately faced social and legal scrutiny. The wish to be treated as a brother is a wish for the social freedom of kinship affection within a romantic relationship — the longing for a covenant that would make what is now constrained socially legitimate and free.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The mother's house (<em>beit immi</em>, H517, my mother's house) appears at 3:4 also as the legitimate social container for love — the beloved would bring the bridegroom there, suggesting that the mother's household was the proper venue for courtship within social convention. The mother as the one who teaches (<em>telammedeni</em>, who would instruct/teach me) is the female wisdom figure of the household — in Proverbs, the mother's teaching is explicitly part of the formation of the young (Prov 1:8: 'hear your father's instruction and do not forsake your mother's teaching'). The spiced wine and pomegranate juice (<em>mine-sheqari min-asis rimmonei</em>) are the luxuries of abundance in the Song's vocabulary of sensory pleasure — wine spiced with aromatics and pressed pomegranate juice were elite beverages in the ancient Near East, the products of craft-level processing of agricultural goods.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The left-hand/right-hand embrace — <em>semalo tachat roshi ve-yamino techabbakeni</em> (his left hand under my head and his right hand embraces me) — repeats 2:6 verbatim. In ancient Near Eastern love poetry, the reclining embrace with one hand as a pillow was a recognized posture of intimacy; Egyptian tomb paintings and iconography show similar embrace postures. The right hand as the arm of action and the left as the support: in ancient Israelite culture, the right hand was the dominant hand for action, protection, and blessing (Gen 48:13-14; Ps 110:1), while the left hand's supportive role under the head creates the image of complete envelopment. The verbatim repetition of 2:6 here is an example of the Song's structural use of refrain-like repetition across the book's arc.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The daughters of Jerusalem adjuration (<em>hishba'ti etkem benot yerushalayim</em>, I adjure you O daughters of Jerusalem) appears for the fourth and final time (2:7, 3:5, 8:4). The earlier two instances invoked 'by the gazelles or the does of the field' — here the animal oath formula is absent, which may signal the maturation of the relationship: the love that needed the protective adjuration is now so firmly established that the oath can stand without the wilderness-animal invocation. The daughters of Jerusalem are the urban audience, the social chorus of the Song who serve as foils for the rural beloved. The content of the adjuration — <em>mah-ta'iru umah-te'oreru et-ha'ahavah ad shetech'pats</em> (why do you stir up or awaken love until it pleases) — consistently warns against forced or premature love. The refrain functions as a wisdom warning embedded in the love poem: love must arise in its own time.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The wilderness-procession image (<em>mi zo't olah min-hamidbar mitrapeket al-dodah</em>, who is this coming up from the wilderness, leaning on her beloved?) repeats the form of 3:6's rhetorical question, but now the figure is identified by her relationship: she is leaning on her beloved, whereas 3:6 was an unidentified pillar of smoke. The apple tree (<em>tappuach</em>, H8598) where the mother aroused her beloved and gave birth — the apple or quince tree appears as a sensory pleasure in 2:3 (sitting under his shadow with great delight) and 2:5 (sustain me with apples). The apple tree as the site of both erotic arousal and birth creates a complex of fertility and love imagery. The wilderness-to-apple-tree movement traces the journey from undomesticated desire to rooted, fruitful intimacy: the beloved comes up from the wilderness and arrives at the cultivated garden tree where the covenant of love was first rooted.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The seal passage (8:6-7) is the theological and poetic climax of the Song. Seals in the ancient Near East were the primary instruments of personal identity and legal authority: cylinder seals (worn around the neck on a cord) or stamp seals (worn as a ring or pendant on the arm) were used to authenticate documents and ownership. To be a seal on someone's heart or arm was to be their most intimate possession and primary identification mark — Jeremiah 22:24 uses the signet ring on the right hand as an image of intimacy with God (though Coniah's signet would be removed). The comparison of love to death (<em>ki azza kamavet ahavah</em>, for love is strong as death) and jealousy to Sheol (<em>qasha kishol qina'ah</em>, jealousy/passion is fierce as Sheol) uses the two most powerful and inescapable forces in human experience as comparators. Death and Sheol could not be resisted in the ancient Near Eastern worldview; to say love is as strong as these is to say it is as absolute and inescapable. <em>Shalhevetyah</em> — the very flame of the LORD — is a rare compound embedding the divine name (YH = abbreviated YHWH) into the word for flame: the flame of divine love burning in the relationship.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The flood-water imagery (<em>mayim rabbim lo yukelu lechabbot et-ha'ahavah</em>, many waters are not able to quench the love; <em>neharot</em>, rivers, cannot drown it) draws on the ANE mythological tradition of the primordial chaos waters as the most threatening force against life and order. In Babylonian cosmology, the primordial Tiamat (chaos-water) was the enemy of the ordered cosmos; in Canaanite mythology, Yam (sea) was the rival of Baal for cosmic dominance. The prophetic literature uses the flood imagery for overwhelming forces of devastation (Isa 8:7-8: the Assyrian flood; Ps 93:3-4: the floods lifting their voices against YHWH). Love that the flood-waters cannot quench is love that withstands the maximum of cosmic threat. The social dimension of v7b — even if a man offered all his house's wealth for love, he would be utterly despised (<em>buz yevuzu lo</em>) — asserts love's non-commercial nature: love cannot be purchased, and the attempt to purchase it invites contempt. Wealth and love exist in incommensurable categories.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The brothers' council scene (8:8-9) introduces the brothers as guardians of their sister's honor — a social institution attested throughout the ancient Near East and biblical narrative. In ancient Israelite law and custom, brothers were the primary protectors of unmarried sisters' sexual honor: Genesis 34 (Dinah's brothers avenging her violation); 2 Samuel 13 (Absalom avenging Tamar); Leviticus 21:3 (the priest may defile himself for an unmarried virgin sister). The little sister (<em>achot lanu qetannah</em>, we have a little sister) who has no breasts yet — a younger sibling not yet at marriageable age — represents the brothers' future social responsibility: they must determine how to prepare for the day when she will be sought in marriage (<em>be-yom sheyedubar bah</em>, in the day she is spoken of/negotiated for). The question 'what shall we do for our sister?' reflects the genuine social deliberation about how to protect and honorably present a younger sibling when the time comes.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The wall/door alternatives present two possible characters for the younger sister: <em>chomah</em> (H2346, wall) as the woman who maintains firm sexual boundaries, and <em>delet</em> (H1817, door) as the woman who is permissive or easily opened. If she is a wall — maintaining honor — the brothers will build upon her a <em>tirat kesef</em> (H2918 + H3701, a turret/battlement of silver): they will add to and honor her fortifications, adorning her honor. If she is a door — sexually permissive — they will enclose her with boards of cedar (<em>natsur aleha luach erez</em>), sealing her off to prevent further access. The cedar board-enclosure represents not punishment but protection: cedar was the most prestigious building material (the temple's cedar paneling, 1 Kings 6:15-16), so enclosing a door with cedar turns it into a wall of the most valuable material. Both responses, wall and door, end in the brothers' protective action, not condemnation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The beloved's self-identification — <em>ani chomah u-shadai kamigdalot</em> (I am a wall and my breasts are like towers) — picks up the brothers' wall/door binary and answers with the wall: she has been the wall throughout. <em>Az hayiti be'einav kemotse'et shalom</em> (thus I became in his eyes as one who finds peace/favor): the word <em>shalom</em> here plays against the name Solomon (<em>shlomoh</em>), creating a word-level pun where the woman's wholeness/peace is the answer to the king's own name. <em>Shalom</em> as the state of wholeness, well-being, and covenant completion is the beloved's self-description after maintaining integrity: she did not yield prematurely, and in finding peace in the bridegroom's eyes she has achieved the wholeness that the Song has been moving toward throughout. In the allegorical reading, Israel's covenant faithfulness to YHWH produces the shalom that is the covenant's promise (Num 6:26).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Solomon's vineyard at <em>Ba'al Hamon</em> (H1174, lord of abundance or lord of the multitude) is an unidentified location — no archaeological site has been securely identified with this name, which suggests either a legendary place or a poetic toponym meaning 'place of great abundance.' The vineyard-keeper arrangement (<em>natan et-ha-kerem la-notreim</em>, he gave the vineyard to the keepers) for a thousand pieces of silver each reflects actual ancient Near Eastern viticulture management: large vineyards were commonly managed through tenant-keeper arrangements where the owner received a fixed portion of the harvest value. Isaiah 7:23 uses the thousand-silver-vine as an image of the most valuable possible vineyard. The economic framework of vineyard value — royal vineyard worth thousands of silver per keeper — sets up the beloved's contrast in v12.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The climax of the vineyard imagery (<em>karmi shelli lefanai</em>, my own vineyard is before me, mine) — the emphatic <em>shelli</em> (mine, my own, from the preposition <em>shel</em> + first person) resolves the vine-narrative that opened the Song. In 1:6, the beloved said 'my own vineyard I have not kept' — she was forced to tend her brothers' vineyards at the expense of her own. Now at the Song's close she asserts full possession: her vineyard is completely her own and is before her (intact, unharvested, fully hers to offer). The thousand to Solomon and the two hundred to the keepers continues the economic framework of v11 but with a different referent: now the beloved herself distributes the vineyard's value according to her own sovereignty, with the two hundred going to 'those who keep the fruit.' In the allegorical reading, Israel's vineyard is YHWH's covenant relationship; the beloved keeping her own vineyard represents covenant faithfulness returned to its proper owner.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The bridegroom's call to the garden-dwelling beloved — <em>hayyoshevet ba-gannim chaverim maqshivim le-qolech hashme'ini</em> (O you who dwell in the gardens, the companions are listening for your voice — let me hear it) — introduces the community of companions (<em>chaverim</em>, H2270, friends/companions) who are also listening for the beloved's voice. This communal dimension — that the beloved's speech is sought not only by the bridegroom but by an audience of companions — mirrors the Song's own social performance context: the poem was sung in community. In Jewish tradition, the Song was sung at weddings and festival celebrations; the companions listening for the beloved's voice are the wedding guests, the community witnessing the love relationship. The beloved who dwells in gardens (<em>yoshevet ba-gannim</em>) has achieved the garden-paradise that was the implicit goal of the Song's pastoral imagery throughout.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Song's final verse — <em>berach dodi vedameh lekha litsvi o le'ofer ha'ayyalim al-harei vesamim</em> (flee, my beloved, and be like a gazelle or a young stag on the mountains of spices) — returns to the gazelle/stag image of 2:9, 2:17, and 4:6, completing the Song's circular structure. The verb <em>berach</em> (flee, H1272) is the same verb used in 2:17 and 4:6 for the stag's departure at dawn — suggesting not a permanent farewell but the movement that precedes a return: the beloved sends the bridegroom out into the mountains of spices (<em>harei vesamim</em>), the fragrant landscape where he will be most himself, with the implicit invitation to return. The Song ends not with consummation described but with anticipation extended — a structural feature consistent with the Song's overall movement through longing, encounter, separation, and renewed longing. This ending is eschatologically charged: the love celebrated throughout the Song is not yet fully realized; its completion lies ahead, in the same direction as the stag bounding over the mountains.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'songofsolomon')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'songofsolomon', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'songofsolomon mkt-context: added {total} verses across ch7-8')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
